column168: On November 1, 2023, two (2) 50-pound bags of UN3378 were punctured by a forklift and released approximately less than one (<1) pound of product to the concrete dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from OMI/E3 to remediate the impacted site. OMI/E3 deconstructed the pallet and removed two (2) 50 pound bags from the pallet. The crew collected the released material with and tools. OMI/E3 placed the released material and two (2) damaged bags into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal.

column168: On November 2, 2023, two (2) 5-gallon pails of UN1993 were crushed in transit and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Indiana Spill Response (ISR) to remediate the impacted site. ISR personnel collected two (2) damaged 5-gallon pails for disposal. Crews then deployed granular absorbent to the impacted trailer floor, concrete and nearby trench drain and worked them in utilizing hand tools. All UN1993 impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal.

column168: On November 2, 2023, one (1) one-gallon pail of UN3264 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Miller Environmental Group (MEG) to remediate the impacted site.  Crews neutralized the impacted surfaces with a sprayer, soda ash solution, and absorbent pads, and they pH tested the surfaces to ensure they were sufficiently neutralized. MEG personnel placed the one (1) impacted 1-gallon pail, used absorbent pads, and any cleanup debris into one (1) 5-gallon bucket that was staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

column168: On November 2, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon jug of UN1824 was punctured and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the dock floor and pallet. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Mid-South Environmental Services (MSES) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed a neutralizing agent to the impacted area. MSES personnel then deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in using hand tools. Crews utilized absorbent pads to collect any residual product from the impacted areas. The empty 5-gallon jug, all spent absorbents, and any cleanup debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and was staged onsite for future disposal.
